role of the novel in nationalism, Mahatma Gandhi and Swami Vivekananda, the Khalsa movement among Sikhs, and nationalist archaeology and the televised Ramayana.Van der Veer offers a new perspective on the importance of religious organization and the role of ritual in the formation of nationalism. His work advances our understanding of contemporary India while also offering significant theoretical insights into one of the most troubling issues of this century.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHinduismxSocial aspectszIndia. 0aIslamxSocial aspectszIndia. 0aNationalismxReligious aspectsxHinduism. 0aNationalismxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aNationalismxReligious aspects. 0aReligion and politicszIndia. 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural & Social. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aVeer, Peter van der, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008256440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091368440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520913684423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520913684/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles